==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scorse
<hw>Scorse</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. It.
<ets>scorsa</ets> a course, and E. <ets>discourse</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Barter; exchange; trade.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And recompensed them with a better <qex>scorse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scorse
<hw>Scorse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Written also <ets>scourse</ets>,
and <ets>scoss</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To barter or
exchange.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To chase.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scorse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scorse
<hw>Scorse</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To deal for the purchase of
anything; to practice barter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scortatory</ent>⟦br⟧
